node.text: I do my best to pay attention to details when I am designing and making furniture and boxes. Here are a few things I did for this jewelry box: straight grain harmonizes with rectilinear shapes, it’s super tight grain (looks better than looser grain would on parts this size), dovetail layouts mirror one another on adjoining parts, pulls are smaller for small drawers than they are for bigger drawers, but they have the same radius, the middle spacer between the stand and case is the same width as the vertical divider in the case and the two outer spacers are the same width as the case sides. I like doing this, but it also drives me crazy at times because I can’t escape it. It’s a quirk, I suppose, to be so obsessed with order and detail but I am putting it to good use.

node.text: Sometimes I do unconventional things, like use miter joints to make small drawers. And miter joints are tricky to plane by hand, so I fit the drawers by sanding them. The drawers will not fit any tighter than they do now. #woodworking #dust #satisfying #whatintarnation #odd #unusual

node.text:
My son and I moved the robot dresser into his room, because the first live lesson for my online box class is tonight, and I need the shop space. I really like this dresser! We joined the plywood boxes with my Festool Domino Joiner. If you look through the top cabinet you’ll see one of the earliest robots I drew. It’s based on a creature my son made up one day while he was at the doctor for his yearly exam: the diabeetus mosqeetus, which he said is how diabeetus (thanks, Wilfred B) is spread. He thought it was hilarious. It was, and still is. Even the medical staff was laughing. On the floor are two early wall cabinets I made and that have lived in his room for a long time. You can see more of my robots over at @thebookofrobots. 
—
If you are interested in my online box class, check out the link in my profile. The lessons are live, but also available on demand (and I have no plans to remove access to them).
